>ethernet and wifi, not just one of them
Without exception (unless you're connecting to a mobile tower) the traffic for your entire house needs to go down your residential link, which the ISP (cable guys) installed in your house some time ago. The only way you're going to get to this link is through a router, which takes the internet from your house and sends it down the magic wire out into the aether. It doesn't matter *how* the traffic reaches the router, be it through a wire (ethernet) or through the air (RF). Of course, for the second, the usual applies of moving your PC closer to the router so the signal doesn't attenuate as much, etc.

But the router must decide which information it sends, and when to drop packets if it's receiving information faster than it can send it out onto the link. I won't bore you with baud rates and the like, but the most important thing is to have the router say, "If I have to choose between sending OP's parents' traffic or OP's, I want to favor OP." - this will speed up your connection significantly when 'contesting' with others.

Everything within those two locations in memory are your string. This construction naturally lends itself to a for-loop:
for(char *p=my_c_string; *p != '\0'; ++p)
This can be simplified, as '\0' is a literal byte 0x00, which is 'false':
for(char *p=my_c_string; *p; ++p)
Which is the most common construction you will see

I urge you to look through documentation and theory, rather than look for code - learning 'why', not just 'how' will help you immensely in the long-run.
